DePIN

Is Cereal a Soup, Socrates? - DePIN's Categorization Problem and the Wisdom of Inclusivity

Dylan Bane

2 days ago ⋅  8 min read

Key Takeaways

  • The DePIN community is debating whether to maintain flexibility for what’s considered a DePIN or prioritize definitional integrity.
  • The problem of defining categories is an age-old debate where the literal definition of a category does not always align with the spirit of the category.
  • The spirit of DePIN is using crypto and blockchain to create real-world value.
  • DePIN should prioritize sector growth at this early stage, maintaining inclusivity for protocols in adjacent spaces that align with DePIN’s spirit.
  • The reputational risk to DePIN by prioritizing inclusivity is overstated. Projects can meet all the rigid criteria for a DePIN and still be fraudulent.

X has erupted into debate over what should be categorized as a DePIN.

One side advocates for inclusivity to foster growth and raise awareness of DePIN at this early stage.

The other side believes that being too broad with categorizing DePIN will dilute the term's meaning, leading to scams latching on to the narrative and building negative connotations for DePIN, similar to what happened with “crypto.”

I argue that leaning towards the first position will maximize the sector’s growth without harming the sector's reputation in the long run.

On Categorization:

A category is a social construct assigning value to a common set of underlying characteristics among various phenomena.

The purpose of a category is utilitarian. Categories help us sort information more efficiently to enhance understanding and communication.

In most cases, we intuitively understand what should be included in a category. Under the sandwich category, we can easily identify a BLT, a PB&J, and grilled cheese as sandwiches without giving it much thought. When asked to define what concretely constitutes a sandwich, we might say it’s a set of ingredients placed in contact with bread.

Once we concretely define a category, the gray area of categories emerges. Under our definition of a sandwich, we would have to add hamburgers to the sandwich category. While few would likely disagree with this categorization, a significant portion of the population would disagree with extending the categorization of sandwiches to hotdogs. Something just feels a little off with calling a hotdog a sandwich. We could try to refine the definition of sandwiches to a set of ingredients between two independent pieces of bread. However, that would exclude a singular slice of a PB&J or any fully continuous sandwich roll from being categorized as a sandwich, which many would also disagree with. Keeping the original definition of a sandwich, we would also be forced to logically include pizza as a sandwich, which most people would likely disagree with. As we can see, defining categories is a problem with thorns.

Another example that gets to the crux of the categorization problem is whether cereal is a soup. Merriam-Webster defines soup as “a liquid food, especially with a meat, fish, or vegetable stock as a base and often containing pieces of solid food.” Under this definition, a bowl of cereal is a soup, as it includes liquid food in milk and pieces of solid food. Once again, however, this categorization just feels wrong. Cereal does not encapsulate the spirit of what we generally consider a soup. Trying to redefine soup to exclude cereal usually results in excluding other soups that most would agree are soups (e.g., if all soups are hot, then gazpacho soup is not a soup. Also, we could heat the milk in cereal to make it soup). We must technically consider cereal as soup even if it does not encapsulate the spirit of soup.

The problem of defining categories is as old as philosophy itself. Much of the early Platonic Dialogues center on Socrates scrutinizing his interlocutor to provide an exact definition for a higher ideal or term. For example, in Hippias Major, Socrates asks the renowned sophist, Hippias, to precisely define beauty. Hippias can point to examples of beauty in specific places, people, and objects, but he fails to define the essence of beauty itself.

Socrates objects:

"You have not answered my question, Hippias. I did not ask what is a beautiful thing, nor did I ask you to tell me one or two of them, but I am asking you what the beautiful is by which all beautiful things become beautiful."

In typical Platonic Dialogue fashion, a concrete definition of the central term at hand, beauty, is never reached in Hippias Major. The problem is that we may intuitively understand the spirit of a category but cannot supply rigid definitions without falling into a wide range of gray-area exceptions that meet the criteria of a definition but fail to capture the spirit of a category.

Defining DePIN vs. the Spirit of DePIN

Just as with sandwiches, soup, and beauty, DePIN faces the classic categorization problem.

At Messari, our working definition of DePIN is: “A protocol that uses token rewards to incentivize the crowdsourcing and building of real-world physical infrastructure networks.”

Nearly everyone would recognize Helium, Hivemapper, and Geodnet as DePINs without giving it much thought. These protocols capture the essence of DePIN, making their categorization easy.

Due to their intangible nature, there may be disagreements about protocols that coordinate file storage or compute. However, they still align with the spirit of DePIN (discussed below), whether categorized as Digital Resource Networks (DRNs) or Decentralized Virtual Infrastructure Networks (DeVIN).

The debate becomes murkier with Bitcoin. Bitcoin uses token rewards to incentivize the deployment of physical infrastructure for mining, fitting our definition of DePIN. Yet, as with cereal being considered a soup, something just feels off with categorizing Bitcoin as a DePIN. The problem is that Bitcoin fails to encapsulate the spirit of DePIN.

So, what is the spirit of DePIN?

DePIN’s spirit is using crypto and blockchain to create real-world value. Helium Mobile creates real-world value by lowering the cost of unlimited consumer data plans. DRNs like Filecoin or Akash create real value by lowering the cost of file storage and compute. DePIN is about making good on crypto’s promise to be useful.

Bitcoin fails to encapsulate the spirit of DePIN since it does not create real-world value in the eyes of most, generating crypto-native value instead. This is why categorizing Bitcoin as DePIN irks so many.

The spirit of a category reflects its essential characteristics. Protocols can reflect the spirit of a category while failing to meet the rigid definition of the category. Conversely, a protocol can align with the rigid definition of a category but fail to encapsulate the category’s spirit.

The Case for Prioritizing Inclusivity

What’s fueling DePIN’s growth as a narrative at this early stage is its spirit. The crypto community demands real use cases and value from crypto. DePIN is the most promising sector to provide this value, and thus, DePIN is becoming synonymous with real-world value enabled by crypto.

What will drive investment, talent, and public awareness into DePIN are not abstract principles like crowdsourcing CapEx costs and automating marketplace backends with smart contracts but the sentiment that DePIN is a revolutionary field creating real value in a way we’ve never seen before uniquely enabled by crypto. If we gain real applications, use cases, and value from founders latching on to that narrative, prioritizing inclusivity for DePIN categorization is more than worthwhile.

Furthermore, strict categorizations can often include protocols like Bitcoin that don’t align with DePIN’s core spirit while excluding others, such as P2P energy markets for real-world assets, that embody it.

What about the scams?

While categories have gray areas, that doesn’t mean everything qualifies. For example, cereal may be considered a soup, but a window clearly is not. Projects not remotely adjacent to DePIN have no justification to align with it, and no one will take them seriously. Inclusivity in DePIN means being flexible with protocols that may not fit strict definitions but still contain DePIN elements and encapsulate its spirit.

Moreover, meeting all DePIN criteria doesn’t prevent scams—no industry is immune to fraud. Enron in energy, Theranos in healthcare, and FTX in crypto are examples. A rigid DePIN definition won’t eliminate fraud from the sector.

Most protocols controversially attaching themselves to DePIN come from the AI, RWA, and data collection fields, which often have legitimate projects involving DePIN elements. These protocols can add significant value to the DePIN narrative. The benefits of growing the sector outweigh the risk of market confusion, and the reputational risk is overstated.

In Conclusion

The DePIN community is debating whether to set strict standards for what qualifies as DePIN or to remain flexible to support growth at this early stage.

Given the challenges of rigid definitions and DePIN's core mission of creating real value, we should stay flexible. This doesn't mean anything can be considered DePIN, but that protocols in adjacent spaces reflecting its spirit shouldn't be excluded.

Over time, I see DePIN evolving from a crypto sector into its own asset class. As this happens, DePIN sub-sectors will crystallize into full-blown DePIN sectors such as Decentralized Energy, Decentralized Wireless, and Decentralized Compute. For now, the priority should be growth, focusing on DePIN’s spirit to attract top founders, talent, and investors rather than getting bogged down in semantics.
